node.text:
Does it ever feel like there aren’t enough hours in a day to accomplish everything you hope to accomplish? 

While balancing work and life in a 24-hour period can be a tricky act, there are simple steps you can take to make your daily routine more manageable in order to achieve more in the short term and long term. Join @dorieclark, an industry expert, author, and speaker, for this webinar to hear her insights into how to make the most of your day, every day. Hosted by @itsterryrice. Link in bio to register.

node.title: Webinar: How To Make The Most Out Your 24 Hours

Don't give up when things go badly. No matter what, just keep moving!

This program will remove the stress and uncertainty that comes with starting a business, and speed up the path to business ownership. Loaded with in-depth guides and added bonuses, this course is what you’ve been waiting for!

node.text:
Workers in tech hubs like San Francisco and New York are familiar with the @allbirds craze of the mid-to-late 2010s, when you couldn’t walk down the street or step into an elevator without seeing the monochromatic merino wool sneakers on the feet of seemingly everyone you met. If they don’t seem as ubiquitous now, that’s likely because they’ve become so commonplace we take them for granted. Allbirds’ growth would indicate that’s probably the case. After launching on the heels of a $120,000 Kickstarter campaign that took place in 2014, the company is now worth a reported $1.7 billion and preparing for a fall 2021 IPO.

Co-founder and CEO Joey Zwillinger has been there since 2015, when he teamed up with New Zealander Tim Brown to create and roll out  the “world’s most comfortable shoe,” created from sustainable merino wool. Five years since its launch, Allbirds has expanded its product offerings beyond the classic Wool Runners to include waterproof sneakers, slip-ons and clothing, and Zwillinger has taken on a large role in shaping the growth of Allbirds.

Read how his morning routine, favorite business book and daily habits make him a better leader in our link in bio.

node.text: When Adrienne Cooper told her boss at a catering company in Chattanooga that she was quitting to build an adults-only roller-skating rink, he said, “Okaaaay. Let me know if you need your job back.” And Cooper admits, “As a 25-year-old Black girl, it was really hard to make headway." But she looked for guidance in unexpected places, and this year @moonlightroller is projected to make $10 million in revenue. Read more about how Cooper made it happen in the link in bio!
